            <p>370. West 33rd St.<lb/>
                New York&#44; 26th Sept. 1883<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. and dear Sir&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>I duly received your<lb/> favor of 10th. July&#44; and have to<lb/> thank you for its interesting contents.<lb/>  Not altogether unconnected with<lb/> a part of it&#44; is the appeal which<lb/> appeared in the &#34;Jewish Chronicle&#34; of<lb/> 7th Inst. in favor of the Jewish Emi<lb/>gration from Roumania to Palestine.<lb/>  It seems to me that Israel has never<lb/> in all its eventful history been more<lb/> on its trial than at the present day.<lb/>  The subject gives me much solici&#34;<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>tude for it is hard to think of so many of<lb/> our brethren and their religious aspirations<lb/> perishing&#44; when some moral and material<lb/> support might save their lives and enable<lb/> them to worship their Maker unfettered.<lb/>  We to whom they have a right to look for<lb/> aid&#44; but who listlessly look on and allow<lb/> it to happen&#44; may be more culpable than<lb/> their cruel persecutors who regard them<lb/> as their foes.  Today I have not time to<lb/> say more&#44; but shall endeavor soon to<lb/> write you further on the subject.<lb/></p>
            <p>By the present I beg to hand you<lb/> a donation of Twenty five Dollars in<lb/> favor of your Synagogue&#44; of which I<lb/> request acceptance.<lb/></p>
            <p>And wishing you all manner of<lb/> prosperity in the New Year&#44; I am&#44; dear Sir&#44; Your&#44;<lb/> David M. Piza.<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev S Morais.<lb/></p>
        </body>
    </text>
